    "body": "Navigation options Published reports come with built-in navigation so readers can jump straight to what interests them — or simply scroll from top to bottom. This page covers what you can control. How report navigation works Your report's table of contents — the ordered list of its sections — drives a navigation menu in the published report: On desktop, readers see a menu of your sections. On mobile, the menu collapses into a tap-to-open dropdown. The current section is highlighted as readers move through the report. You don't build this menu by hand; it follows your sections automatically. Renaming or reordering sections updates it. Section titles are menu labels Each section's title is its label in the navigation menu. Keep titles short and scannable — \"Our Impact\" navigates better than \"A Look Back at Everything We Accomplished Together This Year.\" Hiding sections from the menu Sometimes a section belongs in the flow but not in the menu — a divider, a second gallery, a continuation of the previous topic. You can hide any section from the navigation menu while keeping it in the report; readers still reach it by scrolling. Navigation appearance You can adjust the navigation's color scheme so the menu complements your report's design rather than clashing with a dark or vivid cover. Tips Aim for 5–9 menu items. If your report has fifteen sections, hide the supporting ones so the menu shows just the landmarks. Check the mobile menu. Long section titles truncate sooner on…"
